      <HorSection2
        title="Definition"
        id="Title_Definition"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        <Accordion
        title="Continuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Continuity"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>CONTINUITY</h3>
        A function is said to be <strong>continuous</strong> in a given interval if there is no break in the graph of the function in the entire interval range. At x = a, the following conditions must be satisfied:<br><br>

        <strong>1.</strong> f is defined at x = a<br>
        <strong>2.</strong> The limit of f(x) as x approaches a exists, i.e., <strong>lim f(x) as x → a</strong><br>
        <strong>3.</strong> f(a) = <strong>lim f(x) as x → a</strong>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Discontinuity"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>DISCONTINUITY</h3>
        A function is <strong>discontinuous</strong> at a point if there is a <strong>break, hole, jump,</strong> or <strong>vertical asymptote</strong> at that point. A function is discontinuous if:<br><br>

        <strong>1.</strong> It is undefined at a point<br>
        <strong>2.</strong> The limit does not exist<br>
        <strong>3.</strong> The limit exists but is not equal to the function value <strong>f(a)</strong>
        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>


      <HorSection2
        title="Examples"
        id="Title_Examples"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        <Accordion
        title="Example Continuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Continuity_Example"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>SAMPLE PROBLEM</h3>
        f(x) = x² − 4<br><br>

        <strong>Step 1: Check if f(2) exists</strong><br>
        f(2) = 2² − 4 = 0<br>
        <strong>Defined</strong><br><br>

        <strong>Step 2: Find the limit</strong><br>
        Since it’s a polynomial, we substitute directly:<br>
        lim f(x) as x → 2 = 2² − 4 = 0<br><br>

        <strong>Step 3: Compare</strong><br>
        lim f(x) as x → 2 = f(2)<br><br>

        <strong>Answer:</strong> The function is <strong>continuous</strong> at x = 2. <br>

        <h3>Graph Description</h3>
    When we input the values into a graph, we see a <strong>smooth parabola</strong> that opens upward. The graph is shaped like a “U” and has its <strong>lowest point</strong> at (0, 4).<br><br>

    As x moves toward any value, including x = 2, the function values from the left and right approach the same number. For example, as x approaches 2, the graph approaches 0 from both sides, and the function value at 2 is also 0.<br><br>

    There are <strong>no jumps, holes, or breaks</strong> anywhere on the graph, which shows that the function is <strong>continuous for all real numbers</strong>.

        <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/9ekhfko36i?embed" 
        width="600" 
        height="400" 
        style="border: 1px solid #ccc;">
        </iframe>
        

        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Discontinuity_Example"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>SAMPLE PROBLEM: PIECEWISE FUNCTION</h3>
        <strong>f(x) = </strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;<span>&#123;</span><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;3, if x &lt; 2<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;7, if x ≥ 2<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;<span>&#125;</span><br><br>

        <strong>Step 1: Left-hand limit</strong><br>
        lim f(x) as x → 2⁻ = 3<br><br>

        <strong>Step 2: Right-hand limit</strong><br>
        lim f(x) as x → 2⁺ = 7<br><br>

        <strong>Step 3: Compare</strong><br>
        Since 3 ≠ 7,<br>
        <strong>the limit does not exist</strong> at x = 2.<br>

        <h3>Graph Description: Jump Discontinuity</h3>
    Inputting the values into a graph, we can see that for <strong>x &lt; 2</strong>, the graph stays at <strong>y = 3</strong>, while for <strong>x ≥ 2</strong>, the graph is <strong>y = 7</strong>.<br><br>

    At x = 2, there is an <strong>open circle</strong> at (2, 3) and a <strong>filled dot</strong> at (2, 7).<br><br>

    We can clearly see a <strong>sudden jump</strong> in the graph, which visually represents a <strong>jump discontinuity</strong> because the graph does not connect smoothly at that point.<br>

        <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/mbdquam3ty?embed" 
        width="600" 
        height="400" 
        style="border: 1px solid #ccc;" 
        ></iframe>
        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="Application Of Continuity and Discontinuity"
        id="Title_Application"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        <h3>Applications of Continuity and Discontinuity</h3>
        <strong>Continuity:</strong> Continuous functions are used to model <strong>smooth, predictable behaviors</strong> in real life, such as motion, temperature changes, and economics, where there are no sudden jumps or breaks.<br><br>

        <strong>Discontinuity:</strong> Discontinuous functions are used to represent <strong>sudden changes or abrupt events</strong>, such as switching circuits, stock price jumps, or step functions in engineering and physics. <br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="Applications of Continuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Application_Con"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       <h3>APPLICATIONS OF CONTINUITY</h3>
        <strong>Physics:</strong> Smooth motion of objects.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;When a car moves, it doesn’t suddenly disappear and reappear somewhere else. It moves smoothly from one spot to another. That smooth movement is known as <strong>continuity</strong>.<br><br>

        <strong>Engineering:</strong> Design and constructions.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Engineers design roads, bridges, and roller coasters with smooth curves. If there were sudden breaks or jumps in the design, it would be dangerous.<br><br>

        <strong>Heart Rate Monitoring:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Our heartbeat changes gradually when we exercise. Doctors study smooth patterns in heart rate. Sudden irregular jumps may signal a problem.
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Applications of Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Application_Discon"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>APPLICATIONS OF DISCONTINUITY</h3>
        <strong>Switching Circuits / Electronics:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Turning a device ON/OFF causes current to change abruptly instead of gradually.<br><br>

        <strong>Stock Market:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Sometimes stock prices jump suddenly due to big news or events. This sudden change is a <strong>discontinuity</strong> in the price chart.<br><br>

        <strong>Tax Brackets:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;When income passes a certain limit, the tax rate jumps suddenly. This abrupt change in rate is a real-life example of a <strong>discontinuity</strong>.
        </Accordion>
        </HorSection2>

        <HorSection2
        title="Types of Discontinuity"
        id="Types_Disco"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        <h3>Types of Discontinuity</h3>
    There are two common types of discontinuity in functions:<br><br>

        <strong>1. Removable Discontinuity:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;A <strong>removable discontinuity</strong> happens when a function has a <strong>hole</strong> at a point. <br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;This occurs if the <strong>limit exists</strong> at that point but the <strong>function value</strong> is missing or does not match the limit.<br>

        <strong>2. Essential Discontinuity:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;An <strong>essential discontinuity</strong> occurs when the <strong>limit of the function does not exist (DNE)</strong> as it approaches a point. <br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;This breaks the second condition for continuity: <strong>the limit of f(x) as x → a must exist</strong>.<br><br>
        
        <Accordion
        title="Removable Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Removable_Disco"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>Removable Discontinuity</h3>
        A <strong>removable discontinuity</strong> happens when a function has a <strong>hole</strong> at a point. <br>
        This occurs if the <strong>limit exists</strong> at that point but the <strong>function value</strong> is missing or does not match the limit. <br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Essential Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Essential_Disco"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>Essential Discontinuity</h3>
        An <strong>essential discontinuity</strong> occurs when the <strong>limit of the function does not exist (DNE)</strong> as it approaches a point. <br>
        This breaks the second condition for continuity: <strong>the limit of f(x) as x → a must exist</strong>.<br>
        
        </Accordion>
        </HorSection2>

        <HorSection2
        title="Application Of Essential and Removable Discontinuity"
        id="Title_Application"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >

        <Accordion
        title="Applications of Removable Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Application_RDiscon"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       <h3>Applications of Removable Discontinuity</h3>
        <strong>Mathematical Models / Simulations:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Some formulas are undefined at a single point (like dividing by zero). Redefining the value at that point fixes the <strong>“hole”</strong> in the model.<br><br>

        <strong>Engineering:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;When designing curves (roads, tracks, ramps), a tiny missing point or undefined spot can create a <strong>hole</strong>. Fixing that spot makes the curve smooth again.<br><br>

        <strong>Animation / Video Games:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;A character might jump slightly or a frame might be missing in an animation. Adding the missing frame “fills the hole” just like removing a <strong>removable discontinuity</strong>.
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Applications of Essential Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Application_EDiscon"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>Applications of Essential Discontinuity</h3>
        <strong>Physics:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Modeling phenomena that have sudden spikes or singularities, like electric field strength near a point charge.<br><br>

        <strong>Engineering:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Designing systems where abrupt changes occur, such as switching circuits that jump from one current to another instantly.<br><br>

        <strong>Finance / Economics:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;Representing sudden jumps in stock prices, interest rates, or other financial indicators where the values change abruptly at certain points.
        </Accordion>
        
      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="Types of Essential Discontinuity"
        id="Types_Essential"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        <h3>Jump Essential Discontinuity</h3>
        A <strong>jump essential discontinuity</strong> occurs when the <strong>left-hand limit and right-hand limit</strong> of a function approach <strong>different values</strong> at a point, or when one of the limits does not exist. <br>
        This creates a <strong>sudden jump</strong> in the function, breaking the continuity at that point.<br>

        <h3>Infinite (Essential) Discontinuity</h3>
        An <strong>infinite essential discontinuity</strong> occurs when the <strong>limit of the function from both the left and right</strong> approaches <strong>infinity or negative infinity</strong> at a point. <br>
        This means the function shoots up or down without bound, breaking continuity at that point.<br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="Jump Essential Discontinuity Example: (Click to View)"
        id="Jump_Disco"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>Example: Determining Continuity at x = 2</h3>
    Consider the function defined piecewise as:<br><br>

    <strong>f(x) = </strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;<span>&#123;</span><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(x − 2)², if x &lt; 2<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(x − 2)² + 3, if x ≥ 2<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;<span>&#125;</span><br><br>

    <strong>Step 1: Left-hand limit</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Use the first piece (x &lt; 2) and plug in x = 2:<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;f(x) = (2 − 2)² = 0<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Left-hand limit = 0<br><br>

    <strong>Step 2: Right-hand limit</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Use the second piece (x ≥ 2) and plug in x = 2:<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;f(x) = (2 − 2)² + 3 = 3<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Right-hand limit = 3<br><br>

    <strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Since the left-hand limit ≠ right-hand limit, the function is <strong>discontinuous at x = 2</strong>.

        <h3>Graph Description: Jump Discontinuity</h3>
            Inputting the function into a graph, we can see that the value from the <strong>right</strong> as x approaches 2 is <strong>3</strong>, while from the <strong>left</strong> it is approaching <strong>0</strong>.<br>
            We can clearly see in the graph the visual representation of the <strong>jump discontinuity</strong> as the function <strong>jumps from 0 to 3</strong>.<br>
            Open and filled circles at x = 2 help highlight the jump: <br>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;• Hollow circle at (2,0) for the left-hand value.<br>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;• Filled circle at (2,3) for the right-hand value.<br>

        <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/mx0r8pt9gl?embed" 
        width="600" 
        height="400" 
        style="border: 1px solid #ccc;" 
        ></iframe>
        </Accordion>    

        <Accordion
        title="Infinite Essential Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Infinite_Disco"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>Example: Determine Continuity at x = 4</h3>
    Consider the function:<br><br>

    <strong>f(x) = 1 / (x − 4)</strong><br><br>

    <strong>Step 1: Right-hand limit</strong><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;For x &gt; 4, x - 4 &gt; 0.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;As we input values just to the right of 4, f(x) = 1 / (x - 4) gets larger and larger.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Meaning, it is approaching <strong>positive infinity</strong>.<br><br>

    <strong>Step 2: Left-hand limit</strong><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;For x &lt; 4, x - 4 &lt; 0.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;As we input values just to the left of 4, f(x) = 1 / (x - 4) becomes increasingly negative.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Meaning, it is approaching <strong>negative infinity</strong>.<br><br>

    <strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Since the left-hand limit → −∞ and the right-hand limit → ∞, the function is <strong>infinitely discontinuous</strong> at x = 4.<br><br>

    <h3>Graph Description: Infinite (Essential) Discontinuity</h3>
    In the graph, as we input the function, we can see that it is approaching <strong>infinity</strong> from both the <strong>left</strong> and <strong>right</strong> sides.<br>
    There is a clear <strong>vertical asymptote</strong> at x = 4.<br>
    This visually represents the <strong>infinite discontinuity</strong> as the function shoots up and down without bound near x = 4.<br>
     <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/ihkh9jtntn?embed" 
        width="600" 
        height="400" 
        style="border: 1px solid #ccc;" 
        ></iframe>
        </Accordion>
        
      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="Application Of Jump Essential and Infinite Essential Discontinuity"
        id="Types_Essential"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >

        <Accordion
        title="Applications of Jump Essential Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Application_JED"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>Applications of Jump (Essential) Discontinuity</h3>
        <strong>Digital Logic and Computing:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;A computer bit is either 0 or 1. When a signal changes from "off" to "on," we model it as a <strong>jump</strong>. There is no "0.5" state in binary logic.<br><br>

            <strong>Income Tax Brackets:</strong><br>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;Your marginal tax rate <strong>jumps</strong> to a higher percentage when income crosses certain thresholds.<br><br>

            <strong>Quantum Jumps:</strong><br>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;In physics, electrons in an atom don't "slide" between energy levels. They disappear from one orbit and reappear in another instantly, illustrating a <strong>jump discontinuity</strong> in energy levels.
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Applications of Infinite Essential Discontinuity: (Click to View)"
        id="Application_IED"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       <h3>Applications of Infinite (Essential) Discontinuity</h3>
    <strong>Radio Frequency Interference:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;If you move a microphone close to a speaker, you will get a feedback loop. The screech is an <strong>essential discontinuity</strong> in the sound wave.<br><br>

    <strong>Economics and Finance:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Infinite growth of an investment or extreme market crashes represent sudden, unbounded changes, modeled as <strong>infinite discontinuities</strong>.<br><br>

    <strong>Physics and Engineering:</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;Electric field strength near a point charge or gravitational potential near a massive object can change abruptly, illustrating <strong>infinite discontinuities</strong>.
        </Accordion>
        
      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="Continuity on an Interval"
        id="Interval_Con"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        A function is <strong>continuous over an open interval</strong> if it is continuous at <strong>every point</strong> within that interval.

        <Accordion
        title="Open Interval: (Click to View)"
        id="Interval_Cona"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <strong>Open Interval (a, b):</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;A function is <strong>continuous on (a, b)</strong> if <strong>f(c) = lim x→c f(x)</strong> for every c in (a, b).<br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Closed Interval: (Click to View)"
        id="Interval_Conb"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <strong>Closed Interval [a, b]:</strong><br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;A function is <strong>continuous on [a, b]</strong> if:<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• It is continuous on the open interval (a, b).<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• It is continuous from the right at a: <strong>lim x→a⁺ f(x) = f(a)</strong>.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;• It is continuous from the left at b: <strong>lim x→b⁻ f(x) = f(b)</strong>.
        </Accordion>
        
      </HorSection2>
        <HorSection2
        title="Examples"
        id="Interval_Con"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >

        <Accordion
        title="Example 1: (Click to View)"
        id="Interval_Conex1"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>Example: Interval of Continuity for a Polynomial</h3>
        Determine the interval over which the function <strong>f(x) = x² − 2x + 4</strong> is continuous.<br><br>

        Since the given function is a <strong>polynomial</strong>, it is defined for <strong>all real numbers</strong>.<br>
            A polynomial function is said to be <strong>continuous on the interval (-∞, +∞)</strong>.<br>

            <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/tokkqp0xtk?embed" 
        width="600" 
        height="400" 
        style="border: 1px solid #ccc;" 
        ></iframe>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 2: (Click to View)"
        id="Interval_Conex2"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        <h3>Example: Interval of Continuity for a Rational Function</h3>
        Determine the interval over which the function <strong>f(x) = (x − 2) / (x + 4)</strong> is continuous.<br><br>

        Since the given function is a <strong>rational function</strong>, we must check where the <strong>denominator = 0</strong>.<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;x + 4 = 0 → x = −4<br>
        At x = −4, the function is <strong>undefined</strong>.<br><br>

        Therefore, the function is <strong>continuous everywhere except at x = −4</strong>.<br>
        The interval of continuity is:<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;(-∞, −4) ∪ (−4, +∞)<br>
        <iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/kmcyo8qowr?embed" 
        width="600" 
        height="400" 
        style="border: 1px solid #ccc;" 
        ></iframe>
        </Accordion>
        
      </HorSection2>
      <HorSection2
